    <p>
        Linux is an operating system famous for its usability in servers, it was developed by Linus Torvalds, and is one of the most used Operating Systems in the world
    </p>

    <h5>1. Git</h5>
    <p>
        <strong>Git</strong> is a distributed version control system that allows developers to track changes in their codebase, collaborate with others, and manage project history. It is an essential tool for any software development workflow.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Branching and merging</li>
            <li>Distributed development</li>
            <li>Integration with platforms like GitHub and GitLab</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>2. Vim</h5>
    <p>
        <strong>Vim</strong> is a highly configurable text editor that is perfect for editing code. While it has a steep learning curve, mastering Vim can make you incredibly efficient at navigating and editing files.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Keyboard-centric workflow</li>
            <li>Customizable with plugins</li>
            <li>Lightweight and fast</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>3. Docker</h5>
    <p>
        <strong>Docker</strong> is a containerization platform that allows developers to package applications and their dependencies into containers. This ensures that your application runs consistently across different environments.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Lightweight containers</li>
            <li>Environment consistency</li>
            <li>Integration with CI/CD pipelines</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>4. tmux</h5>
    <p>
        <strong>tmux</strong> is a terminal multiplexer that allows you to manage multiple terminal sessions within a single window. It is especially useful for remote development and multitasking.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Split terminal windows</li>
            <li>Persistent sessions</li>
            <li>Customizable key bindings</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>5. Bash and Shell Scripting</h5>
    <p>
        Bash and other shell scripting tools are essential for automating repetitive tasks, managing system configurations, and writing deployment scripts.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Task automation</li>
            <li>System administration</li>
            <li>Integration with other Linux tools</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>6. htop</h5>
    <p>
        <strong>htop</strong> is an interactive process viewer for Linux. It provides a real-time view of system resource usage, making it easier to monitor and manage processes.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Real-time system monitoring</li>
            <li>Process management</li>
            <li>Customizable interface</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>7. curl</h5>
    <p>
        <strong>curl</strong> is a command-line tool for transferring data over various network protocols. It is widely used for testing APIs, downloading files, and debugging network issues.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Key Features:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Supports multiple protocols (HTTP, FTP, etc.)</li>
            <li>Command-line simplicity</li>
            <li>Useful for API testing</li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <h5>Conclusion</h5>
    <p>
        Linux offers a rich ecosystem of tools that can significantly improve your software development workflow. By mastering tools like Git, Vim, Docker, and tmux, you can become a more efficient and productive developer. Whether you're writing code, managing servers, or debugging applications, these tools are indispensable for modern software development.
    </p>

